    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-09T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-09T03:00:00-05:00" n="976"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d976">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.52/55: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-09T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >March 9, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 9—6:56 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>83. Embassy’s 80, March 6, noon; Department’s 43, March 8, 6 p.m.—perpetual
                    leaseholds.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Foreign Office informs me that our draft note and letter will be submitted
                        together with the British documents to the Privy Council March 17 and that
                        signature and exchange will take place on the 18th or 19th.<note n="48"
                            xml:id="d976fn48">Signature took place March 25; Executive Agreement
                            Series No. 104, or 50 Stat. 1611.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>I have filed no reservation to the effect that any right of American
                        leaseholders which may be legally enforceable cannot be compromised by this
                        settlement. There seems to be nothing to be gained by such action
                        particularly as the Japanese Government proposes to introduce a law which
                        would invalidate all perpetual leaseholds on <pb facs="0832" n="824"
                            xml:id="pg_824"/> April 1, 1942. Furthermore, the Japanese Government
                        would not accept a formal reservation of that nature.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The Department’s press release is appreciated by the Foreign
                        Office.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
